solution:
1. Determine the atomic number of helium: Helium has an atomic number of 2.

2. Calculate the ionization energy using the formula for the ionization energy in the Bohr model:
   Ionization energy = - \frac{Z^{2} \cdot 13.6 \, \text{eV}}{n^{2}}
   where Z is the atomic number and n is the energy level of the electron being removed (n = 1 for singly ionized).

3. Plug in the values into the formula:
   Ionization energy = - \frac{2^{2} \cdot 13.6 \, \text{eV}}{1^{2}}
   Ionization energy = - \frac{4 \cdot 13.6 \, \text{eV}}{1}
   Ionization energy = -54.4 \, \text{eV}

4. Convert the ionization energy to kJ/mol:
   1 eV = 96.485 kJ/mol
   Ionization energy = 54.4 eV * 96.485 kJ/mol
   Ionization energy = 5.25 kJ/mol

Therefore, the ionization energy of singly ionized helium is -54.4 eV or 5.25 kJ/mol.

