solution:
1. Use Wien's displacement law, which states that the peak wavelength of a blackbody radiation curve is inversely proportional to the temperature of the object:

λ_{\text{max}} = \frac{b}{T}

where:
λ_{\text{max}} = maximum wavelength of the blackbody radiation
b = Wien's displacement constant = 2.897 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m} \cdot \mathrm{K}
T = temperature in Kelvin

2. Substitute the given values into the formula:

λ_{\text{max}} = \frac{2.897 \times 10^{-3} \mathrm{~m} \cdot \mathrm{K}}{288 \mathrm{~K}} = 1 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}

Therefore, the maximum wavelength of the earth's blackbody radiation is $1 \times 10^{-5} \mathrm{~m}$.

